  {
    "id": "Ugxatgu-wYWwZ_QSl_l4AaABAg",
    "author": "@ericwazhung",
    "author_channel_id": "UCtE3RqZeq9S_bSCNdJLvulg",
    "text": "When I was a kid in the 90's I got a flatbed plotter, which truly fascinated me... Its motors were stationary like this, but the pulley system is, in fact, cartesian. One motor for X and another for Y. \n\nI had always thought CoreXY was just a newfangled name for that design until I saw your model, here.\n\n It seems both motors have to move, in CoreXY, to move the head along one axis... which reminds me a bit of wall-hanging plotters. The math is somewhat complicated to convert cartesian coordinates to pythagorean(?). But, I guess, in the end, a fast computer/CPU can handle it, so it really doesn't matter.\nThough, I wonder if it makes for weird resolution-effects. Say the stepper motors are 1.8deg/step, in a cartesian system each step might amount to 0.1mm. But on a system like this, it seems like it might have higher resolution in some areas, and lower in others.\n\nInteresting, anyhow. And as always, great explanation!",
    "likes": 1,
    "published_at": "2024-08-14T04:27:11Z",
    "reply_count": 1,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "Ugxatgu-wYWwZ_QSl_l4AaABAg.A76G_W-GKiEA76fbpFBTVv",
        "author": "@ThinkingandTinkering",
        "author_channel_id": "UC4AkVj-qnJxNtKuz3rkq16A",
        "text": "the math does get a bit more complicated - verging on calculus - but not too much to be honest",
        "likes": 1,
        "published_at": "2024-08-14T08:14:41Z"
      }
    ]
  },
